1) The Hobbit — J.R.R. Tolkien (1937)  
   - Brief description: A classic quest-adventure in which Bilbo Baggins is drawn into a dangerous journey with dwarves, trolls, and dragons.  
   - Why it fits: If you enjoy the imaginative, timeless children’s/fantasy feel of Peter Pan, The Jungle Book, and The Marvelous Land of Oz in your collection, The Hobbit delivers a richly imagined world and warm adventure-driven storytelling you’ll likely enjoy.

2) Brave New World — Aldous Huxley (1932 / many modern editions)  
   - Brief description: A foundational dystopian novel that examines a technologically managed society, consumerism, and the cost of stability.  
   - Why it fits: Your library contains classic social critiques and dystopian-leaning titles (for example, Fahrenheit 451 and Animal Farm appear as close matches in the profile). If you like thought-provoking classics that interrogate society and human nature, this one is a strong match.

3) Normal People — Sally Rooney (2019)  
   - Brief description: A contemporary literary novel following the complex, intimate relationship between two young people over several years.  
   - Why it fits: You have character-driven, relationship-focused novels (Pride and Prejudice, Wuthering Heights, and modern literary titles like Harold Fry). Normal People’s psychological depth and focus on social class and intimacy should appeal to that taste for emotionally precise, character-centered fiction.

4) The Hitchhiker’s Guide to the Galaxy — Douglas Adams (1979)  
   - Brief description: A comedic science-fiction romp that follows Arthur Dent’s absurd, cosmic misadventures after Earth’s destruction.  
   - Why it fits: If you like the whimsical, surreal and satirical side of classics such as Alice’s Adventures in Wonderland and the satirical bite of Gulliver’s Travels, Adams’ book offers similar humor and inventive absurdity—just in a sci-fi setting.

5) The Alchemist — Paulo Coelho (1988)  
   - Brief description: A short, allegorical novel about a shepherd’s journey in search of personal destiny; a meditation on signs, dreams, and self-discovery.  
   - Why it fits: Given your interest in pilgrimage/transformative journeys (The Unlikely Pilgrimage of Harold Fry) and fable-like storytelling (The Jungle Book, Gulliver’s Travels), The Alchemist’s spiritual quest and parable-style narrative should resonate.

Diversity rationale
- I selected five books across different moods and genres — high fantasy (Tolkien), classic dystopia (Huxley), contemporary literary fiction (Rooney), comic science fiction (Adams), and allegorical fable (Coelho). That keeps recommendations closely tied to the themes and styles already in your uploads (classics, character-driven novels, whimsy/satire, and journey narratives) while giving a variety of reading experiences and authors.

